This question looks scary because of the letters.

But it’s REALLY just:

take pieces
move pieces
combine pieces

That’s it.

STEP 1 — Understand the layout

You are given TWO bytes:

X1
X1 : B7 B6 B5 B4 A7 A6 A5 A4
X2
X2 : B3 B2 B1 B0 A3 A2 A1 A0
Visualize the bit positions

A byte has 8 positions:

bit7 bit6 bit5 bit4 bit3 bit2 bit1 bit0

So X1 actually means:

bit7 bit6 bit5 bit4 bit3 bit2 bit1 bit0
 B7   B6   B5   B4   A7   A6   A5   A4

Notice:

Part	Location
B7 B6 B5 B4	upper nibble
A7 A6 A5 A4	lower nibble

X2 means:

bit7 bit6 bit5 bit4 bit3 bit2 bit1 bit0
 B3   B2   B1   B0   A3   A2   A1   A0

Again:

Part	Location
B3 B2 B1 B0	upper nibble
A3 A2 A1 A0	lower nibble
GOAL

Build:

A = A7 A6 A5 A4 A3 A2 A1 A0

and:

B = B7 B6 B5 B4 B3 B2 B1 B0
PART 1 — Build A

We need:

A7 A6 A5 A4 A3 A2 A1 A0
Where are A7 A6 A5 A4?

Look at X1:

X1 : B7 B6 B5 B4 A7 A6 A5 A4

They are on the RIGHT side.

RIGHT side = lower nibble.

Keep lower nibble

Use:

X1 & 0x0F

Why?

Because:

0x0F = 00001111

keeps ONLY lower 4 bits.

Example visually

Suppose:

X1 = 10100110

AND:

10100110
00001111
--------
00000110

Only lower nibble survives.

But we need these bits in the LEFT side of A

Currently:

0000 A7 A6 A5 A4

We need:

A7 A6 A5 A4 0000

So move them LEFT:

(X1 & 0x0F) << 4
Now get A3 A2 A1 A0

Look at X2:

X2 : B3 B2 B1 B0 A3 A2 A1 A0

Again they are already lower nibble.

So:

X2 & 0x0F

gets:

A3 A2 A1 A0
Final step — combine both halves

Use OR:

((X1 & 0x0F) << 4) | (X2 & 0x0F)
Final answer for A

A=((X1&0x0F)<<4)∣(X2&0x0F)

PART 2 — Build B

Need:

B7 B6 B5 B4 B3 B2 B1 B0
Where is B7 B6 B5 B4?

Look at X1:

X1 : B7 B6 B5 B4 A7 A6 A5 A4

They are already in upper nibble.

Keep upper nibble

Use:

X1 & 0xF0

because:

0xF0 = 11110000

keeps upper nibble.

Where is B3 B2 B1 B0?

Look at X2:

X2 : B3 B2 B1 B0 A3 A2 A1 A0

They are in upper nibble.

But we need them in LOWER nibble.

Move them right

Use:

(X2 & 0xF0) >> 4
Visual example

Suppose:

10110000

Shift right 4:

00001011

Now B3 B2 B1 B0 are in lower nibble.

Combine both halves

Use OR:

(X1 & 0xF0) | ((X2 & 0xF0) >> 4)
Final answer for B

B=(X1&0xF0)∣((X2&0xF0)>>4)

The BIG beginner realization

This entire question is ONLY:

Action	Operation
keep lower nibble	& 0x0F
keep upper nibble	& 0xF0
move left	<< 4
move right	>> 4
combine pieces	`

That’s literally the whole exercise.

Ex 2 :
Swap/toggle the value of bit 6 of the given byte X
X = b7 b6 b5 b4 b3 b2 b1 b0
Needs to become:
B = b7 not(b6) b5 b4 b3 b2 b1 b0
Answer: (formula, can be in different steps)
B = ……………………………………….. explain em thisone

This question is asking you to:

flip ONLY bit 6

Meaning:

Current bit	New bit
0	1
1	0

This operation is called:

toggle
Original byte
X = b7 b6 b5 b4 b3 b2 b1 b0

Need:

B = b7 not(b6) b5 b4 b3 b2 b1 b0

So ONLY bit 6 changes.

Everything else stays the same.

Which operator toggles bits?

The special operator for toggling is:

XOR

which is:

^
Why XOR works

XOR rule:

Bit	XOR 1	Result
0	1	1
1	1	0

So XOR with 1 flips the bit.

Step 1 — Create mask for bit 6

Bit 6 means:

01000000

which is:

0x40
Step 2 — XOR with mask
B = X ^ 0x40

This flips ONLY bit 6.

Visual example

Suppose:

X = 01100101

Bit 6 is currently:

1
XOR with mask
01100101
01000000
--------
00100101

Bit 6 flipped from:

1 → 0

Everything else stayed the same.

Another example

Suppose:

00100101

XOR:

00100101
01000000
--------
01100101

Bit 6 flipped:

0 → 1
Final answer

B=X⊕0x40

or in C/Python notation:

B = X ^ 0x40
Beginner mental model
Operation	Meaning
&	keep bits
`	`
^	toggle/flip bits
<<	move left
>>	move right
SUPER IMPORTANT shortcut

If exam says:

Question wording	Operation
check bit	&
turn ON bit	`
turn OFF bit	& ~mask
toggle bit	^

This pattern repeats constantly in bit exercises.

